photo.description: Ms. ownership inscription of the Monastery of San Giorgio Maggiore: "Est S[anc]ti Georgij Maioris Ven[etiarum]" The Monastery of San Giorgio was established in 982, when the Benedictine monk, Giovanni Morosini asked the doge Tribuno Memmo to donate the whole island of San Giorgio Maggiore (in Venice) for a Monastery. Morosini drained the island's marshes next to the church to get the ground for building, and founded the Monastery of San Giorgio Maggiore, and became its first abbot. In the early 19th century, after the Republic fell, the monastery was almost suppressed and the island became a free port with a new harbour built in 1812. It became the home of Venice's artillery. It is now the headquarters of the Cini Foundation arts centre, known for its library and is also home to the Teatro Verde open-air theatre. Established heading: San Giorgio maggiore (Monastery : Venice, Italy) Penn Libraries call number: IC55 M2693 564s 1581 Penn Libraries catalog record All images from this book

photo.description: Ownership inscription of the Benedictine abbey of Saints Ulrich and Afra, Augsburg, Germany (now defunct). The abbey was founded (in pre-existing premises, displacing a group of cathedral canons) in the early 11th century and was secularized in 1802. The monks were briefly exiled during the Reformation (1537-1548), but were granted the status of a free imperial abbey in 1577 by Emperor Rudolph II. (The Bishops of Augsburg objected and the legal wrangle continued until 1644, when the monks won.) Cf. the entry at the Klöster im Bayern website. Established form: St. Ulrich und Afra (Benedictine abbey : Augsburg, Germany) Penn Libraries call number: GC5 W9526 555a All images from this book

photo.description: First inscription (red ink): Fr[ater] Bartholome[us] Kapffer [pro]fess[us] in Fultenbach. .1.5.55. [Autograph of Bartholomeus Kapffer, a monk professed at the Benedictine house Kloster Fultenbach in Holzheim, Bavaria, Germany. The monastery was founded in 739 and secularized in 1803. Its fortunes declined precipitously in the 15th century, to the point where it came under the administration of the bishopric of Augsburg. In 1471 the Benedictine abbey of Saints Ulrich and Afra, Augsburg, successfully undertook to revive the foundation until the wars of the 16th century stomped it again.] Second inscription (dark ink): Dono datus Hic liber ab eodem, Casparo Ei[...]o[?] in pign[us] amoris. Anno [etc.] 57. [Ms. inscription recording the gift of this book to Caspar {Illegible} by "the same man" (presumably Brother Bartholomeus) in 1557.] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 W9526 555a All images from this book

photo.description: "Castone di Rezzonico" Ownership inscription of Carlo Castone della Torre di Rezzonico (1742-1796), a cousin of Carlo Rezzonico (Pope Clement XIII). photo.description: H. T. Whately Ch. Ch. [Henry Thomas Whately (1822?-1879), Christ Church, Oxford. Earned his B.A. in 1845 and M.A. in 1847; vicar of Kington Co., Hereford from 1860 until his death in 1879. His full entry in the Alumni Oxonienses (1715-1886) is here.] A. Lamont Probably Austin Lamont (1905-1969), son of Thomas W. Lamont, banker at JP Morgan after whom Harvard's Lamont Library is named. According to this article in Anesthesiology, Austin Lamont was "originally planning to study classic Latin and Greek at the New College, Oxford University, England, [but] he changed his mind while still on the steamship headed for Europe." He instead studied science and became a doctor and professor of anesthesiology at the University of Pennsylvania School of Medicine (1947-mid1960s). Austin and his 2nd wife Bodine were Philadelphia elites and associated with other prominent Philadelphians Carl and Laura Zigrosser. Carl Zigrosser was a prints curator at the Philadelphia Museum of Art and member of the Print Club (Philadelphia). A finding aid to Zigrosser's papers is available here. Other examples of Austin Lamont's autograph. Stamp of the Department of Classical Studies Department, University of Pennsylvania Penn Libraries call number: GrC An135 1813

photo.description: Bookplate "Gulielmus Burrell, Arm. de Beckenham in Com. Cantii" with arms belonging to Sir William Burrell, 2nd Baronet, 1732-1796. Cf. Wikipedia and Burrell's entry in the Dictionary of National Biography. Established heading: Burrell, William, Sir, 1732-1796 After his death in Jan.1796 Burrell's library went to auction in May of that year. This title is listed as no. 415 in the auction catalogue of his library. Cf. A catalogue of the town-library of the late Sir William Burrell ... In 1773 he married Sophia Raymond, later known as Lady Sophia Burrell, a poet and dramatist (1750?-1802) whose signature dated "May 1796" also appears in this volume. After the death of her first husband William in Jan 1796, Lady Burrell married Rev. William Clay in 1797 probably the same "Wm. Clay" (1765-1836) whose signature also appears in this volume. Cf. DNB. photo.description: Signature dated May 1796 of Sophia Burrell (1750?-1802), poet and dramatist (known as Lady Burrell) . She was the wife of Sir William Burrell, (1732-1796) whose armorial bookplate can also be found in this volume. It is unclear who or when the inscription "bought at Robsons" was added. It is written in a darker ink than that of the Sophia Burrell's signature. James Robson (1733-1806) was one of the booksellers listed on the catalogue of William Burrell's library sold on May 2 1796 following Burrell's death in Jan. of that year. Cf. here. The autograph of her second husband, William Clay, appears on the title page. Did Sophia purchase the volume back from her late husband William Burrell's auctioned library in May 1796 or did she just keep the book as she was preparing to sell her husband's estate inscribing it at that time? Maybe the Robson's refers to the original purchaser of the book, her first husband William Burrell. Established heading: Burrell, Sophia, Lady, 1750?-1802 Penn Libraries call number: GrC An135 1554 All images from this book

photo.description: Bookplate of Harold Greenhill (1893-1968) over that of Charles Dorrien Established heading: Greenhill, Harold, 1893-1968 Harold Greenhill, a Chicago book collector and president of William P. Green Co., was born in Chicago, Illinois, in 1893 and graduated from the University of Illinois in 1917 with a degree in mechanical engineering. He was a member of the Caxton Club from 1948 until his death and served two terms on the Club's Council. Greenhill was also a member of the Grolier Club. He died in Rhinelander, Wisconsin on 15 October 1968. Many of his books were bought by Bradley H. Martin and sold at Martin's sale. Greenhill's books are also found at Princeton University and at the Newberry Library. Penn Libraries call number: IC55 G9315 Eg602d All images from this book

While there is no established heading for Charles Evans, he may be a bird enthusiast who made the first recorded sighting of the Evening Grosbeak in Cinnaminson, N.J., apparently the most southern sighting of this bird to date in 1916. photo.description: Inscription: James Moon His Book 1773 James Moon is most likely the grandson of a Quaker Englishman from Bristol named James Moon who immigrated to Bucks County, PA. with his wife Joan and their six children in 1682. The family is said to perhaps have sailed with William Penn on the "Welcome" and landed in New Castle, DE. Cf. worldconnect.genealogy.rootsweb.ancestry.com/cgi-bin/igm.... The family then settled in Fallsington, in Falls Township, Bucks County, near Morrisville, and eventually purchased a 125 acre farm that is still in the family today (now called Snipes Farm). The family was actively involved with the Falls Monthly Meeting. There are two headings for James Moon of Bucks County in VIAF. The correct one probably is Moon, James, but there are no dates so it is difficult to tell. The James Moon who inscribed these pamphlets may be the grandson of James Moon Sr., and he remained in Bucks County and began to grow and sell ornamental trees in 1767, beginning a tradition of horticulture in the family. He was born in 1713 and is the eldest son of Roger Moon (James Moon Sr.'s youngest child) and Ann Nutt Moon. He died in 1796. Cf. pagenweb.org/~bucks/BIOS_DAVIS/moonfamily.html The autographs of James Moon look like a match to this one found here. This document (and there are several others for sale by this auction house) is a Quaker slave manumission from Bucks County, PA. in 1777. It is a Quaker document declaring a particular slave to be freed on a particular date in the future, and James Moon has signed these documents as a witness. Penn Libraries call number: EC7 A100 721j 1761 All images from this book
photo.title: James Moon (1713-1796)
